<HEADLINE>
<P>
BISHOPS' PANEL ON GAY ISSUES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 As a gay man, I found the article "Episcopal Bishops Panel Completes Study on 
Gay Issues" (Aug. 6) interesting, encouraging and a little amusing. 
</P>
<P>
 Although I have to give the bishops credit for "wrestling with" the issue, the 
baby was thrown out with the bathwater long ago.I, along with many of my gay 
brothers and sisters, have stopped worrying about what the churches think of 
us. Most of us have gone beyond the narrow doctrines of religion and have found 
self-acceptance and strength within our own communities. It is as one clergyman 
who unsuccessfully fought the intolerance in his own church once said to me: 
"Why would you want to be a part of a church which hated you?" I don't. 
</P>
<P>
 GREGORY N. AMOUR 
</P>
<P>
 West Hollywood 
</P>
</TEXT>
